#: ../../source/searching.rst:610
msgid "Search Syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:612
msgid "In the persistent search box, single words generally retrieve large sets. To narrow a search, you can use multiple words. Koha automatically uses the 'and' Boolean operator to create a set of records matching your input. When you want to narrow the search to an author or a title or a subject or some other specific field or use a Boolean operator, there isn't an obvious way to accomplish that specificity. The library user can, of course, go to the Advanced Search page; however, if you know how to construct a CCL search, you can achieve more specificity while using the persistent search box on any page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:622
msgid "There is a specific order to the CCL search syntax. Although it can be used for simple searches, it is an especially effective way to perform complex searches, as it affords you a great deal of control over your search results. To construct a CCL search, first enter a desired index code, then an equal sign, followed by your search word(s). Following are examples of simple CCL searches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:629
msgid "ti=principles of accounting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:631
msgid "au=brown joseph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:633
msgid "su=poetry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:635
msgid "su-na=Shakespeare"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:637
msgid "kw=marlin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:639
msgid "You can refine your search by combining search terms with Boolean operators 'and', 'or', or 'not'. Following are examples of searches using Boolean operators."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:643
msgid "ti=principles of accounting and au=brown joseph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:645
msgid "su=poetry not su-na=Shakespeare"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:647
msgid "kw=communication and su=debate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:649
msgid "You can also choose to search for things that start with a character or series of characters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:652
msgid "ti,first-in-subfield=C (will show you all titles that start with the letter 'C')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:655
msgid "Other string location searches can be performed with the following keywords:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:658
msgid "rtrn : right truncation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:660
msgid "ltrn : left truncation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:662
msgid "lrtrn : left and right truncation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:664
msgid "st-date : type date"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:666
msgid "st-numeric : type number (integer)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:668
msgid "ext : exact search on whole subfield (does not work with icu)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:670
msgid "phr : search on phrase anywhere in the subfield"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:672
msgid "startswithnt : subfield starts with"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/searching.rst:674
msgid "Using specific indexes and Boolean operators are not the only way a search can be refined. You can also refine your search as a phrase when looking for a title, author, or subject. The syntax for this search is *index,phr=search words*."
msgstr ""

